@Ollie wrote:

[quote=“Sean, post:51, topic:27831”]by caching it means a cache of the value of the variable so it can be accessed quicker (like in a register). This is all fine and well in certain situations for the performance improvements but when there is alot of concurrent modification the cached version in the register can fall behind the actual value of the variable. By declaring a field volitile it is telling the vm to ALWAYS fetch the REAL value of this variable, rather than rely on a cached value of it when it was last checked.

item.title: Whats the difference
item.dc:creator: @Krichevskoy Krichevskoy
item.description:
@Krichevskoy wrote:

Javacisnotrecognized:

I r Trying to lern wat a byt3 iz.

Ref: http://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/datatypes.html

byte: The byte data type is an 8-bit signed two's complement integer. It has a minimum value of -128 and a maximum value of 127 (inclusive). The byte data type can be useful for saving memory in large arrays, where the memory savings actually matters. They can also be used in place of int where their limits help to clarify your code; the fact that a variable's range is limited can serve as a form of documentation.

If you didn’t know, Java is one of the most accessibly documented languages in existence. Sun provides excellent tutorials on all aspects of their language, complete with example code and practice exercises, in one easy-to-use package on their website.

http://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/

Javacisnotrecognized:

What the hell is the point of having an entire board, full of Java experts, devoted to Java programming, where the experts won’t even tell you about primitive Types??@!

The above link is the reason that we seem unhelpful. You’re asking questions that, while perfectly reasonable to anyone beginning to learn Java, are readily available to anyone willing to search for “java tutorial” on Google.

Examples of good questions are the initial few here: what exactly do access levels mean (because the Java tutorial uses terminology that you probably don’t know yet), what are the static/volatile modifiers, how about those weird brackets, etc. Those are things beyond the scope of “Hello, World”-level Java and we’re happy to help anyone along the path to proficiency

However, the primitive data types are very basic. So when you ask us about those, it looks like you haven’t even tried to find out for yourself. This may not be true - I know I’ve read tutorials for things and still been totally clueless afterward - but there are so many people who just don’t make the effort that general unhelpfulness becomes the standard reaction to anyone asking basic questions.

It might help alleviate the problem if you would post something along the lines of

I've looked at the Java tutorial's definition and a few other sites off Google, but I'm still having trouble understanding what a byte is.

Similarly, responding to legitimate questions with

White Castle:

What the fuck dude, just go look on Google. =/

is really uncalled for.
